		<item>
		<title>An unrepresentative Congress</title>
		<link>http://theppl.us/blog/898</link>
		<comments>http://theppl.us/blog/898#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 06 Jul 2012 15:53:59 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Corey Conner</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Blog]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://theppl.us/?p=898</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Despite the United States’ history as a representative democracy, the current congress isn’t much like its people. Cord Jefferson, with Good, recently looked at what congress would look like if it really represented America. Almost 100 years after the first woman was elected to congress, there are only 91 women serving compared to 448 men. [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div id="attachment_930" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width: 586px"><a href="http://theppl.us/an-unrepresentative-congress/2044748271_b809bdf62c_z/" rel="attachment wp-att-930"><img class=" wp-image-930 " title="US Capitol Building" src="http://theppl.us/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/2044748271_b809bdf62c_z.jpeg" alt="US Capitol Building" width="576" height="384" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Photo Courtesy of Andrew Malone</p></div>
<p>Despite the United States’ history as a representative democracy, the current congress isn’t much like its people.</p>
<p>Cord Jefferson, with <a href="http://good.is">Good</a>, recently looked at <a href="http://www.good.is/post/infographic-what-congress-would-look-like-if-it-really-represented-america/">what congress would look like if it really represented America</a>.</p>
<p>Almost 100 years after<a href="http://womenincongress.house.gov/"> the first woman was elected to congress</a>, there are only 91 women serving compared to 448 men.</p>
<p>Racial diversity is also lacking. Caucasians are over-represented, while every other race is under-represented.</p>
<p>As Jefferson pointed out, even economically, Congress doesn&#8217;t represent the norm.</p>
<blockquote><p>Our senators and representatives are also wholly different from most Americans in terms of wealth. We&#8217;ve <a href="http://www.good.is/post/your-new-congressmen-are-richer-than-pretty-much-everyone-you-know/">said this before</a>, but it bears repeating: The average American&#8217;s net worth is <a href="http://money.cnn.com/2011/03/24/pf/financial_crisis_outcome/">$96,000</a>. But the average Senator&#8217;s net worth? <a href="http://www.opensecrets.org/pfds/averages.php">$13.4 million</a>. For House members that sum drops to &#8220;just&#8221; $5 million.</p></blockquote>
<p><a href="http://www.usatoday.com/news/washington/story/2011-11-15/congress-wealthy-1/51216626/1">57 members of Congress are part of the 1%</a>, but will a candidate&#8217;s personal finances trump the <a href="http://www.gallup.com/poll/1675/most-important-problem.aspx">all important issues of jobs and the economy at large</a>?</p>
<p>Not in the opinion of <a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/post/why-people-hate-congress-in-one-chart/2011/12/28/gIQA1IyUMP_blog.html">Washington Post columnist Aaron Blake</a>.</p>
<blockquote><p>So should we expect Americans to start voting out the wealthy and voting in the middle class? Not exactly.</p>
<p>The realities of campaigning make it a rich person’s enterprise. Candidates often have to have enough wealth so that they can leave their jobs to campaign full-time, and it always helps to be able to put millions of your own money into a campaign.</p>
<p>But the fact that people are learning that their Congress is getting richer, even in tough economic times, bodes ill for whatever hope legislators had for returning to the good graces of the American public.</p></blockquote>
<p>Despite this, occupy-inspired candidates, such as<a href="http://nymag.com/daily/intel/2012/06/george-martinez-occupy-wall-street-congress-ny1-debate.html"> George Martinez in New York&#8217;s 7th congressional district</a>, are struggling to move past protest movements and into electoral politics.</p>
<p>So, while Congress&#8217;s personal wealth may not inspire much voter enthusiasm, it could help sustain the values of a <a href="http://www.latimes.com/news/nation/nationnow/la-na-nn-the-end-of-occupy-wall-street-20120610,0,7439790.story">struggling Occupy movement</a>. As the rich become richer and the rest, poorer, the discrepancies between Congress and the people may become exasperated as they move to tackle issues such as <a href="http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/2012/0425/Student-loans-Will-Congress-s-remedy-favor-middle-class-over-poor">$1 trillion in student loan debt</a> heading into election season.</p>
<p>Historically, Congress hasn&#8217;t been an edifice of diversity, and there is no indication that drastic change is around the corner. However,<a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/05/opinion/krugman-states-of-depression.html"> a prolonged state of depression</a> might cause voters to look for a more accurate representation of themselves.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
]]></content:encoded>
